# Why and When Do Exceptions Occur:
    Let’s know the Common Scenarios Leading to Exceptions

    1. Null Pointer Exceptions
        This is a very common one. A NullPointerException (NPE) occurs when you try to use an object that hasn't been initialized
        yet—kind of like trying to use a car that doesn’t have an engine!
        For example:
            String name = null;
            System.out.println(name.length()); // Throws NullPointerException

    2. Array Index Out of Bounds
        Arrays in Java have fixed lengths, just like the number of seats in a train. If you try to access an index outside that range,
        Java will throw an ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException. It’s like trying to sit in a seat that isn't there.
        For example:
            int[] numbers = {1, 2, 3};
            System.out.println(numbers[3]); // Throws ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException

    3. Arithmetic Exceptions
        Math is great, but not every operation is allowed—even in Java. If you try to divide by zero, for example, you'll get an ArithmeticException.
        For example:
            int result = 10 / 0; // Throws ArithmeticException: / by zero

    4. Number Format Exceptions
        Have you ever tried converting a word into a number? Java will throw a NumberFormatException if you try to turn non-numeric text into a number.
        For example:
            String value = "abc";
            int number = Integer.parseInt(value); // Throws NumberFormatException

# Key Points to Remember:
    1. Null Pointer Issues: Occur when you use something that hasn’t been given a value yet. Always check if an object is set before
                            calling its methods (for example, don’t call .length() on a text that might be empty).
    2. Array Index Errors: Happen when you try to access a spot in an array that doesn’t exist (for example, asking for the fourth item
                           in a 3-element array). Remember that array positions start at 0 and go up to length – 1.
    3. Division by Zero: You can’t divide a number by zero. Before dividing, make sure the value you’re dividing by is not zero.
    4. Invalid Number Conversions: If you try to turn text like “abc” into a number, it fails. Always check that a string contains
                                   only digits before calling something like Integer.parseInt().

# Common Interview Questions & Sample Answers:

    Q1: What is a Null Pointer Exception and how can you avoid it?
     A: This happens when you call a method or access data on an object that was never given a value. To avoid it,
